{{Other people|Edward Abbott}} {{Infobox person | name = Edward Abbott | birth_date = {{Birth date|1841|07|15}} | birth_place = [[Farmington, Maine]], U.S. | death_date = {{Death year and age|1908|1841}} | death_place = | resting_place = Pine Grove Cemetery in [[Brunswick, Maine]], U.S. | occupation = Minister, Priest, Journalist, Author | father = [[Jacob Abbott]] (1803-1879) }}
'''Edward Abbott''' (July 15, 1841<ref>{{cite web|title=United States Passport Applications, 1795-1925|url=https://familysearch.org/ark:/61903/1:1:QV5Y-VWJB|website=FamilySearch|accessdate=22 April 2016}}</ref> &ndash; 1908) was an [[United States|American]] [[Minister (Christianity)|minister]] (later [[priest]]), journalist, and author.
== Early life == On July 15, 1841, Abbott was born in [[Farmington, Maine]]. Abbott's father was [[Jacob Abbott]] (1803-1879). <ref name="findagrave_abbott_1841">{{cite web |url=https://www.findagrave.com/cgi-bin/fg.cgi?page=gr&GRid=46916232 |title=Edward Abbott (1841) |work=[[Find a Grave]]|accessdate=June 1, 2017}}</ref>
== Education == Abbott graduated in 1860 at the [[New York University|University of New York]], studied from 1860 to 1862 at the [[Andover Theological Seminary]],<ref name="LeonardMarquis1908"/> and in 1863 served in the [[United States Sanitary Commission]] at [[Washington, D.C.|Washington]] with the [[Army of the Potomac]].
== Career == Abbott was ordained in 1863 to the [[Congregational]] ministry, and was [[pastor]] of Pilgrim Church, [[Cambridge, Massachusetts]], from 1865 to 1869. From 1869 to 1878 he was associate editor of ''[[The Congregationalist]]'', and from 1878 to 1888 editor of the ''[[Literary World]]'', whose direction he again assumed in 1895. In 1879 he was ordained a priest of the [[Episcopal Church (United States)|Episcopal Church]] and appointed rector of St. James's parish, Cambridge. His publications include ''The Conversations of Jesus'' (1875) and ''[[Phillips Brooks]]'' (1900).
