{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2013}} {{Use Indian English|date=July 2013}} {{Infobox cricketer | name = Rajesh Chauhan | image = Cricket_no_pic.png | country = India | batting = Right-hand bat | bowling = Right-arm offbreak | deliveries = balls | columns = 2 | column1 = [[Test cricket|Tests]] | matches1 = 21 | runs1 = 98 | bat avg1 = 7.00 | 100s/50s1 = -/- | top score1 = 23 | deliveries1 = 4749 | wickets1 = 47
| bowl avg1 = 39.51 | fivefor1 = - | tenfor1 = - | best bowling1 = 4/48 | catches/stumpings1 = 12/- | column2 = [[One Day International|ODIs]] | matches2 = 35 | runs2 = 132 | bat avg2 = 10.15 | 100s/50s2 = -/- | top score2 = 32 | deliveries2 = 1634 | wickets2 = 29 | bowl avg2 = 41.93 | fivefor2 = - | tenfor2 = n/a | best bowling2 = 3/29 | catches/stumpings2 = 10/- | date = 4 February | year = 2006 | source = <ref>[http://content-aus.cricinfo.com/ci/content/player/27622.html ESPN Cricketinfo Rajesh Chauhan, India]</ref>}}
'''Rajesh Chauhan''' {{audio|Rajesh_Chauhan.ogg|pronunciation}} (born 19 December 1966 in [[Ranchi]], [[Bihar]]) is a former [[India]]n [[cricket]]er who played in 21 [[Test cricket|Tests]] and 35 [[One Day International|ODI]]s from 1993 to 1998. He was part of the Indian spin trio of [[Anil Kumble|Kumble]] ([[Leg break]]) -[[Venkatapathy Raju|Raju]] ([[Left arm orthodox]])-Chauhan ([[Off break]]), in the 1990s.
Although his own contributions were only of limited value, [[Indian cricket team|India]] lost none of the 21 Tests in which he played. The record, for which he is perhaps remembered most for his last-over six off [[Saqlain Mushtaq]] at Karachi in 1997, which sealed a four-wicket win for India against Pakistan.
In April 2007 he was seriously injured in a car accident. He suffered multiple fractures as well as bruising on his leg, back, hand and head. He currently resides in [[Bhilai]] - [[Chhattisgarh]] running a business. He is now PRO in [[Bhilai Steel Plant]].<ref>[http://www.espncricinfo.com/india/content/story/288672.html Rajesh Chauhan injured in road accident]</ref><ref>[http://cricketnext.in.com/news/excricketer-rajesh-chuahan-injured/24169-13.html Ex-cricketer Rajesh Chauhan injured]</ref>
His father Govind Raja Chauhan, who lived in [[Ranchi]], was also a cricketer and played [[Ranji Trophy]] in 1957 & [[Duleep Trophy]] in 1964.<ref name=kgk/> Their ancestral village is [[Vidi]] in [[Kutch]] and he belongs to a small community known as [[Kutch Gurjar Kshatriya]].<ref name=kgk/><ref>{{cite news|title=कच्छ गुर्जर समाज का मिलन समारोह|url=http://www.bhaskar.com/article/CHH-OTH-1601509-2533633.html|accessdate=2 August 2013|newspaper=Dainik Bhaskar|date=1 November 2011|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140407065449/http://www.bhaskar.com/article/CHH-OTH-1601509-2533633.html|archivedate=7 April 2014|df=dmy-all}}</ref>Rajesh also served as Chairman of All-India Youth Wing of Kutch Gurjar Kshatriya community for years 1993–96 and is an active social member of the community.<ref name=kgk>Kutch Gurjar Kshatriya Samaj : A brief History & Glory by Raja Pawan Jethwa. (2007)</ref>
On 7 July 2014 suffered a massive cardiac arrest at his residence in Bhilai, however, survived.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.abplive.in/sports/2014/07/07/article358062.ece/Cricketer-Rajesh-Chauhan-suffers-cardiac-arrest#.U7uADfmSzTo|publisher=ABP Live |title=Cricketer Rajesh Chauhan suffers cardiac arrest| accessdate=7 July 2014 }}</ref>
